  {
    "id": 5,
    "title": "Geopolitiks Snacks — April 2, 2026",
    "date": "2026-04-02",
    "tags": ["NATO", "Tariffs", "Iran", "Ukraine", "Tech"],
    "fresh": false,
    "content": "**Geopolitiks Snacks** — April 2, 2026\n\n---\n\n## 🏳️ Trump Threatens to Quit NATO Over Iran War (Casual Wednesday Energy)\n\nWho would've thought that fighting an optional war in the Middle East would eventually strain the alliance that's supposed to back you up? Trump announced he is \"absolutely\" considering **withdrawing the US from NATO** after allies refused to join the US-Israel war on Iran. He also said US forces would end operations in Iran \"very soon,\" which is either a peace signal or a negotiating tactic—his team clarified nothing.\n\n- NATO, a 32-country alliance built specifically so America wouldn't have to fight alone, is now apparently optional if the allies don't show up to America's optional war. Checks out.\n- \"Very soon\" is doing a lot of diplomatic heavy lifting here. It's been 32+ days. \"Soon\" is a flexible word.\n- The fact that this announcement coincided with Liberation Day tariff anniversary is either deeply symbolic or a complete coincidence. Probably both.\n\n**Sources:** [The Guardian: Trump considers NATO withdrawal](https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/apr/01/trump-says-he-is-absolutely-considering-withdrawing-us-from-nato)\n\n---\n\n## 📉 Liberation Day 2.0: Markets Down 10%, S&P Has Worst Week Since COVID\n\nHappy anniversary, Liberation Day! To celebrate, Trump enacted **new global tariffs** — minimum 10% on everything, 73% on China — and the S&P 500 fell over **10% in two days**, the worst week since the COVID recession of 2020. Auto imports got indefinite exemptions. Everything else did not.\n\n- The Supreme Court ruled the original tariffs illegal in February. A refund process affecting $170B is ongoing. The administration's response was to add more tariffs. Bold pivot.\n- A 73% tariff on Chinese goods while simultaneously postponing the summit with Xi Jinping is either an incredible negotiating strategy or a complete train wreck in slow motion. We're going with \"probably the second one.\"\n- Global supply chains had already rerouted around the first tariff regime. Now they have to reroute around the new one. The logistics industry is printing money.\n\n**Sources:** [Al Jazeera: Trump Tariff Effects](https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2026/2/24/new-trump-tariffs-take-effect-days-after-supreme-court-decision) | [Tax Foundation](https://taxfoundation.org/research/all/federal/trump-tariffs-trade-war/)\n\n---\n\n## 🛢️ Oil Hits $100/Barrel as Strait of Hormuz Stays Closed\n\nGreat news: oil is testing **$100 per barrel** as the Strait of Hormuz — responsible for 20% of global energy supply — remains effectively closed to commercial tankers. The EIA revised its 2026 WTI oil forecast upward by $20. Kuwait and the UAE are cutting production because storage is full and they can't ship.\n\n- 6-7 million barrels per day are offline. The global economy is essentially running a live experiment in what happens when you remove a fifth of the world's oil supply. The results are: expensive.\n- $4 gas was the protest trigger. $100 oil is going to make $4 gas look nostalgic.\n- Meanwhile, the countries most affected by high oil prices are also the countries who depend most on cheap energy to run their AI data centers. Someone somewhere is rethinking their power purchase agreements.\n\n**Sources:** [IMF Blog: Middle East War Energy Effects](https://www.imf.org/en/blogs/articles/2026/03/30/how-the-war-in-the-middle-east-is-affecting-energy-trade-and-finance) | [CNBC: Oil Prices](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/03/28/oil-gas-prices-iran-war-hormuz.html)\n\n---\n\n## 🇺🇦 Ukraine Is Actually Gaining Ground (Russia Disagrees, Naturally)\n\nPlot twist: in a war where Russian state media has been announcing victories for three years, Ukraine's commander says the country **captured more territory in February than it lost**. Russia simultaneously declared the \"liberation\" of Luhansk oblast, where Ukraine controls 0.2% of territory. Ukrainian drones struck an oil refinery in Ufa on April 2. A Trump-Zelenskyy peace proposal is reportedly 90-95% agreed upon.\n\n- Russia announcing Luhansk is \"liberated\" while Ukraine holds 0.2% of it is a masterclass in narrative management.\n- 90-95% of a peace deal agreed is also 5-10% from being a deal. That last 5-10% is doing a lot of work.\n- Ukrainian drones hitting a refinery in Ufa (deep inside Russia) is not a small thing. That's 1,300 km from the front line.\n\n**Sources:** [Kyiv Independent: Ukraine territorial gains](https://kyivindependent.com/ukraine-captured-more-territory-than-it-lost-to-russia-over-febraury-2026-syrskyi-says/) | [Russia Matters: War Report April 1](https://www.russiamatters.org/news/russia-ukraine-war-report-card/russia-ukraine-war-report-card-april-1-2026)\n\n---\n\n## 🏗️ Big Tech Is Spending $650 Billion on AI This Year (That's a Lot of Data Centers)\n\nIn case you were wondering why energy grids are stressed: Meta, Microsoft, Alphabet, and Amazon are collectively planning to spend **$635–665 billion** in capital expenditures in 2026, almost entirely for AI infrastructure. Microsoft alone is running at a $145B annual capex run rate (67% increase from 2025). Meta is putting in $115-135B.\n\n- For context: the entire US interstate highway system cost $500B in today's dollars and took 35 years. Big Tech is spending more than that, on AI servers, in one calendar year.\n- The semiconductor industry is on track to hit **$1 trillion in sales** in 2026 — driven almost entirely by AI chip demand — and industry leaders say their top concern is now tariffs. The irony is thick.\n- This is what \"the AI arms race\" actually looks like in balance sheet terms: six companies spending the GDP of a medium-sized country on compute, simultaneously.\n\n**Sources:** [Tech Startups: April 1 2026](https://techstartups.com/2026/04/01/top-tech-news-today-april-1-2026/) | [Tom's Hardware: Semiconductor $1T](https://www.tomshardware.com/tech-industry/semiconductors/semiconductor-industry-on-track-to-hit-usd1-trillion-in-sales-in-2026-sia-predicts-bumper-forecast-follows-usd791-7-billion-haul-for-2025)\n\n---\n\n## 📌 Sources\n\n- [The Guardian: Trump considers NATO withdrawal](https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/apr/01/trump-says-he-is-absolutely-considering-withdrawing-us-from-nato)\n- [Al Jazeera: New Trump Tariffs Take Effect](https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2026/2/24/new-trump-tariffs-take-effect-days-after-supreme-court-decision)\n- [Tax Foundation: Trump Tariffs Analysis](https://taxfoundation.org/research/all/federal/trump-tariffs-trade-war/)\n- [IMF Blog: Middle East War Energy Impact](https://www.imf.org/en/blogs/articles/2026/03/30/how-the-war-in-the-middle-east-is-affecting-energy-trade-and-finance)\n- [CNBC: Oil and Gas Prices Iran War](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/03/28/oil-gas-prices-iran-war-hormuz.html)\n- [Kyiv Independent: Ukraine Gains February 2026](https://kyivindependent.com/ukraine-captured-more-territory-than-it-lost-to-russia-over-febraury-2026-syrskyi-says/)\n- [Russia Matters: War Report Card April 1](https://www.russiamatters.org/news/russia-ukraine-war-report-card/russia-ukraine-war-report-card-april-1-2026)\n- [Tech Startups: Top News April 1 2026](https://techstartups.com/2026/04/01/top-tech-news-today-april-1-2026/)\n- [Tom's Hardware: Semiconductor Industry $1T](https://www.tomshardware.com/tech-industry/semiconductors/semiconductor-industry-on-track-to-hit-usd1-trillion-in-sales-in-2026-sia-predicts-bumper-forecast-follows-usd791-7-billion-haul-for-2025)\n"
  },
