    "id": 4,
    "title": "Geopolitiks Snacks — April 1, 2026",
    "date": "2026-04-01",
    "tags": ["USA", "China", "AI", "Amazon", "Robots"],
    "fresh": false,
    "content": "**Geopolitiks Snacks** — April 1, 2026\n\n---\n\n## 📵 Trump Ghosts Xi Jinping, Reschedules the Most Important Meeting on Earth\n\nWho would've thought that the man who invented \"Liberation Day\" would also just... cancel a summit with the President of China two days before it was supposed to happen? The Trump-Xi Beijing summit, set for March 31–April 2, has been postponed at Trump's request. No new date confirmed.\n\n- Treasury Secretary Bessent and China's Vice Premier He Lifeng met in Paris ahead of the summit and called it \"constructive,\" which is diplomatic code for \"we disagree about everything but didn't throw anything\"\n- China's FM Wang Yi said 2026 should be a \"landmark year\" for US-China relations. It's April 1st. Landmark status: TBD.\n- The October 2025 trade truce is technically still in force, which means approximately zero things have been resolved — they've just agreed not to publicly explode it yet\n- November midterms are ticking, the Iran war is on, and now the world's two largest economies are playing phone tag\n\n*\"Landmark year\" is going to hit differently in December.* 🗓️💀\n\n**Sources:** [Washington Post: Trump Postpones Xi Summit](https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2026/03/08/china-us-relations-trump-xi-summit-wang-yi/) | [Bessent-He Lifeng Paris Talks](https://www.reuters.com/world/us-china-talks-paris-2026-03-28/)\n\n---\n\n## 🧪 AI Labs Are Now Just Leaking Their Own Models to Generate Hype\n\nOh great, it's another week of competing AI lab drama — Anthropic's mystery flagship model (codenamed \"Capybara\" or \"Mythos,\" pick your cryptid) has been leaking like a sieve, scoring \"dramatically higher\" on coding, reasoning, and cybersecurity benchmarks than Claude 4.6 Opus. Meanwhile OpenAI's next model, codenamed \"Spud,\" finished pretraining on March 25.\n\n- Anthropic's new model tier scores so high on cybersecurity benchmarks that presumably it is now a hacking threat. Cool feature.\n- OpenAI quietly shelved its \"adult mode\" ChatGPT project AND Sora video generation this week. That's two products being walked back simultaneously. The year is going great.\n- OpenAI's \"Spud\" has finished pretraining which means the GPT-5.x upgrade cycle is about to start again and your current workflows will be obsolete by summer. Get comfortable.\n- Anthropic also launched a monthly \"What We Shipped\" livestream starting April 7 — AI labs are now doing product drops like sneaker brands\n\n*At this point every 90 days you get a new model that makes the last one feel like a Nokia.* 📱🔥\n\n**Sources:** [The Neuron: AI Weekend Digest Mar 28-29](https://www.theneuron.ai/ai-news-digests/-around-the-horn-digest-everything-that-happened-in-ai-this-weekend-march-28-29-2026/)\n\n---\n\n## 🦾 Two-Year-Old Robotics Startup Now Worth More Than Most Airlines\n\nShocking: a company that's been alive for 24 months and makes no revenue is being valued at **$11 billion**. Physical Intelligence — founded by ex-Google DeepMind researchers — is in talks to raise ~$1 billion in a new funding round. The robots-that-actually-work sector is apparently printing money now.\n\n- Physical Intelligence builds foundation models for physical robots — basically GPT but for robot hands — which is either the most important technology being built right now or the most expensive science project, depending on your level of existential dread\n- For context: $11B puts this two-year-old company ahead of Spirit Airlines, Peloton, and several mid-sized countries' GDP. For a company that has not shipped a commercial product. Totally normal.\n- Also this week: Agile Robots (Munich-based) announced a strategic partnership with Google DeepMind to integrate Gemini Robotics foundation models. The robot-brain supply chain is consolidating fast.\n\n*The robots don't have products yet but they DO have PowerPoints valued at $11 billion. We're so back.* 🤖💰\n\n**Sources:** [Bloomberg: Physical Intelligence $11B Valuation](https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2026-03-27/ex-deepmind-staffers-robotics-startup-in-talks-for-11-billion-valuation)\n\n---\n\n## 🚕 Waymo Is Now Half a Million Rides a Week and We've Completely Normalized This\n\nRemember when \"self-driving cars\" was a punchline? Waymo is now doing **500,000 paid robotaxi rides per week** — doubling in under a quarter — and the target is 1 million weekly rides by end of year. The future crept up on us while we were arguing about it.\n\n- Zoox expanded to Austin and Miami this week, quadrupling its San Francisco service area. The self-driving footprint is quietly becoming national.\n- Uber announced **Europe's first robotaxi service** launching in Zagreb, partnering with Pony AI and Verne. Zagreb. The robotaxi capital of Europe is apparently Zagreb. You heard it here.\n- None of these companies are profitable yet, all of them have raised billions, and every week half a million people just... get in a car with no driver and accept it completely\n\n*\"Are you sure there's no driver?\" is going to be the \"wait there's no CD drive?\" of this decade.* 🚗🤖\n\n**Sources:** [The Neuron: Waymo 500K Rides](https://www.theneuron.ai/ai-news-digests/-around-the-horn-digest-everything-that-happened-in-ai-this-weekend-march-28-29-2026/) | [Reuters: Uber Zagreb Robotaxi](https://www.reuters.com/technology/uber-europe-robotaxi-zagreb-2026-03-29/)\n\n---\n\n## 🏭 Amazon Is Buying Entire Chunks of Oregon to Build AI Data Centers\n\nJust casually, Amazon purchased **1,300 acres** of land near the Columbia River in Boardman, Oregon — and is planning to spend **$8 to $12 billion** on 16 to 20 data center buildings that could consume approximately **1 gigawatt of power**. A gigawatt. For one campus.\n\n- To put a gigawatt in context: that's roughly the output of a nuclear power plant, now dedicated to making sure your AI coding assistant can answer questions slightly faster\n- This is separate from the Fauna Robotics and Rivr acquisitions this week. Amazon is buying land, robots, AND model startups simultaneously. The diversification strategy is \"everything.\"\n- The Columbia River data center campus would be among the largest ever built. The Pacific Northwest's power grid is about to have a very interesting few years.\n\n*\"Just need a little more compute\" — Big Tech, while purchasing the equivalent of a small city* ⚡🏗️\n\n**Sources:** [Tech Startups: Amazon Oregon Land Purchase](https://techstartups.com/2026/03/31/top-tech-news-today-march-31-2026/)\n\n---\n\n## ⚓ The US Just Funded a $9.25B Startup That Builds Autonomous Warships\n\nOh good, we're now putting the \"autonomous\" in \"autonomous naval vessels.\" Saronic, a startup building autonomous ships, closed a **$1.75 billion funding round** this week, doubling its valuation to **$9.25 billion**. The defense-tech boom is officially indistinguishable from a sci-fi arms race.\n\n- Saronic builds unmanned surface vessels — robotic ships — primarily for US defense applications. Ghost fleet, but make it startup.\n- $9.25 billion for autonomous warships means the investor thesis is either \"defense budgets are eternal\" or \"we are prepared for whatever comes next.\" Possibly both.\n- The maritime defense funding wave comes as the Strait of Hormuz situation continues making shipping companies very, very nervous — creating a tidy market opportunity for robotic ships that don't need crews in harm's way\n\n*\"It's not a warship, it's a maritime AI solution.\"* 🚢🤖💸\n\n**Sources:** [Tech Startups: Saronic $1.75B Raise](https://techstartups.com/2026/03/31/top-tech-news-today-march-31-2026/)\n\n---\n\n## 🗳️ AI VCs Are Now Running a $100M Political Operation for the Midterms\n\nDavid Sacks — the White House AI Czar — is backing a new political operation called **Innovation Council Action** that's preparing to spend **$100+ million** in the 2026 midterms on candidates who support Trump's deregulatory AI agenda. The tech-to-government pipeline has completed its loop and is now a full circle.\n\n- The campaign explicitly targets AI-friendly, deregulation-supportive candidates. The framing is \"pro-innovation.\" The subtext is \"please don't regulate us.\"\n- $100 million in midterm spending from a single-issue AI PAC would make it one of the largest single-issue outside spenders in the cycle. For context, this is more than the entire GDP of several Pacific island nations, spent to make sure your chatbot doesn't have guardrails.\n- This comes as the AI industry is simultaneously facing EU regulation pressure, state-level bills in 14 US states, and a Supreme Court still processing what \"AI liability\" even means\n\n*The robots can't vote yet, so VCs are doing it for them.* 🗳️🤖💰\n\n**Sources:** [Tech Startups: Innovation Council Action $100M](https://techstartups.com/2026/03/30/top-tech-news-today-march-30-2026/)\n\n---\n\n## 📌 Sources\n\n- [Washington Post: China Hopes 2026 Is a Landmark Year for US Relations](https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2026/03/08/china-us-relations-trump-xi-summit-wang-yi/)\n- [The Neuron: Everything That Happened in AI Mar 28–29 2026](https://www.theneuron.ai/ai-news-digests/-around-the-horn-digest-everything-that-happened-in-ai-this-weekend-march-28-29-2026/)\n- [Bloomberg: Physical Intelligence $11B Valuation Talks](https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2026-03-27/ex-deepmind-staffers-robotics-startup-in-talks-for-11-billion-valuation)\n- [Tech Startups: Top Tech News March 31, 2026](https://techstartups.com/2026/03/31/top-tech-news-today-march-31-2026/)\n- [Tech Startups: Top Tech News March 30, 2026](https://techstartups.com/2026/03/30/top-tech-news-today-march-30-2026/)\n"
  },
